# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: crack-the-whip
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:crack-the-whip/crack-the-whip-steven-universe-p01] During the course of the series, 160 episodes of *Steven Universe* aired over five seasons, between November 4, 2013, and January 21, 2019.
[src:crack-the-whip/crack-the-whip-steven-universe-p01] A television film, *Steven Universe: The Movie*, was released on September 2, 2019, following the fifth and final season.
[src:crack-the-whip/crack-the-whip-steven-universe-p01] A concluding limited series, *Steven Universe Future*, premiered on December 7, 2019, and ended on March 27, 2020.
[src:crack-the-whip/crack-the-whip-steven-universe-p01] The order and length of the first three seasons is inconsistent between official sources; this list uses the "intended order" of the episodes as specified by co–executive producer Ian Jones-Quartey, which re-orders six episodes from the first two seasons compared to the broadcast order.
[src:crack-the-whip/crack-the-whip-steven-universe-p01] 26 half-hours (52 episodes) were produced for Season 1; this list includes a 53rd, "Say Uncle," which was produced and aired as part of Season 2, but which in terms of story chronology is placed by Jones-Quartey's list late in Season 1.
[src:crack-the-whip/crack-the-whip-steven-universe-p01] Episode premieres initially occurred weekly on Monday nights, but moved to Wednesday nights beginning with the episode "Steven the Sword Fighter," then to Thursday nights beginning with the episode "Coach Steven".
[src:crack-the-whip/crack-the-whip-steven-universe-p01] The episodes "Open Book", "Shirt Club", and "Story for Steven" were bumped to air during the second season in order to facilitate airing the final 'arc' of season one over five consecutive nights.
[src:crack-the-whip/crack-the-whip-steven-universe-p01] Ian Jones-Quartey was the supervising director for each episode, but is uncredited in "Say Uncle".
[src:crack-the-whip/crack-the-whip-steven-universe-p01] Season 2 and Season 3 were produced as one season of 26 half-hours, comprising 49 regular episodes, 1 double-length special, and 6 shorts.
[src:crack-the-whip/crack-the-whip-steven-universe-p01] When the season was officially split in two after the fact, 26 of the regular episodes and the shorts were aired as "Season 2".
[src:crack-the-whip/crack-the-whip-steven-universe-p01] This included "Say Uncle," but as previously noted, this list moves that episode to Season 1.
[src:crack-the-whip/crack-the-whip-steven-universe-p02] Jasmin Lai is the art director for every episode, with Elle Michalka co-directing "Full Disclosure".
[src:crack-the-whip/crack-the-whip-steven-universe-p02] A television film based on the series, titled *Steven Universe: The Movie*, premiered on Cartoon Network on September 2, 2019; its production was first announced on July 21, 2018, at San Diego Comic-Con with the release of its first teaser trailer.
[src:crack-the-whip/crack-the-whip-steven-universe-p02] The film is a musical, featuring musical collaborations with Chance the Rapper, Estelle, Gallant, Aimee Mann, James Fauntleroy, Macie Stewart, Mike Krol, and others, and takes place two years after the events of "Change Your Mind".
[src:crack-the-whip/crack-the-whip-steven-universe-p02] A limited series, *Steven Universe Future*, intended to serve as an epilogue to the main series, premiered on December 7, 2019.
[src:crack-the-whip/crack-the-whip-steven-universe-p03] All six digital shorts combined make up one full production code of the second season (1031-058).
[src:crack-the-whip/crack-the-whip-steven-universe-p03] All five of these shorts combined make up one full production code of the fourth season (1040-112).
[src:crack-the-whip/crack-the-whip-steven-universe-p03] These shorts are written solely by Rebecca Sugar and are animated by Chromosphere Studio.
[src:crack-the-whip/crack-the-whip-steven-universe-p03] A series of public service announcement shorts where the Crystal Gems teach the audience about anti-racism.
[src:crack-the-whip/crack-the-whip-steven-universe-p03] All of the shorts are written by Rebecca Sugar and Ian Jones-Quartey, and animated by Chromosphere Studio.
[src:crack-the-whip/crack-the-whip-steven-universe-p03] Depending on the customer's region, *Steven Universe* is available through various video on demand services such as Hulu, Google Play, iTunes, Amazon Video, and Microsoft Movies & TV.
[src:crack-the-whip/crack-the-whip-steven-universe-p03] In North America, Warner Home Video has Steven Universe on DVD in several formats: single-disc compilations of select episodes, two *Complete Season* releases, and a *Complete Collection* box set.
[src:crack-the-whip/crack-the-whip-steven-universe-p03] Madman Entertainment followed a similar pattern in Australia.
[src:crack-the-whip/crack-the-whip-steven-universe-p03] They released two compilation DVDs, five Complete Season DVD and Blu-ray releases, and a standalone DVD of *The Movie*.
[src:crack-the-whip/crack-the-whip-steven-universe-p03] Madman's season releases use an alternative episode order and lack all the bonus material included in the North American versions.
[src:crack-the-whip/crack-the-whip-steven-universe-p03] In the United Kingdom, Manga Entertainment released the first season on DVD and Blu-ray on February 24, 2020.
[src:crack-the-whip/crack-the-whip-steven-universe-p03] This version used Madman's episode order but included the bonus material from the American DVD.
[src:crack-the-whip/crack-the-whip-steven-universe-p03] The second season was planned to be released on March 16, 2020, but was cancelled before release.
[src:crack-the-whip/crack-the-whip-steven-universe-p03] Several episodes are re-ordered on home video.
[src:crack-the-whip/crack-the-whip-steven-universe-p03] In the table below, the episodes are listed in the order they appear on the disc, and are numbered according to the episode tables above.
[src:crack-the-whip/crack-the-whip] Unlike musical chairs the game is not won by the last to hold on.
[src:crack-the-whip/crack-the-whip] Instead, those shucked along the way are welcome to rejoin the game so long as they can hang on, with competition among them to resume as close to the current tail as they can, to minimize the likelihood of being thrown off again at its end.
[src:crack-the-whip/crack-the-whip] There is no objective to the game, which was illustrated in Winslow Homer's 1872 painting of boys joyously plunged in *Snap the Whip*, other than having fun and enjoying its physical thrills.
[src:crack-the-whip/crack-the-whip] It experienced a distinct wave of popularity in the 1930s and 1940s in the United States at public skating rinks, and was often featured in Hollywood movies of that time.
[src:crack-the-whip/musical-chairs] A set of **chairs** is arranged in a circle with one fewer chair than the number of players (i.e. nine players would use eight chairs).
[src:crack-the-whip/musical-chairs] While music plays, the contestants walk around the set of chairs.
[src:crack-the-whip/musical-chairs] When the music stops abruptly, all players must find their own individual chair to sit on.
[src:crack-the-whip/musical-chairs] The player who fails to sit on a chair is eliminated.
[src:crack-the-whip/musical-chairs] One chair is then removed for the next round, and the process repeats until only one player remains and is declared the winner.
[src:crack-the-whip/musical-chairs] The origins of the game's name as "Trip to Jerusalem" is disputed.
[src:crack-the-whip/musical-chairs] However, it is known to come from its German name *Reise nach Jerusalem* ("Journey to Jerusalem").
[src:crack-the-whip/musical-chairs] One theory suggests that the name was inspired by the Crusades, wherein several heavy losses were incurred.
[src:crack-the-whip/musical-chairs] Another theory suggests that it was inspired by the immigration of Jews from the diaspora to Palestine, wherein it is stated that spaces on ships taking the Jews to the said land were limited.
[src:crack-the-whip/musical-chairs] None of these theories have been confirmed.
[src:crack-the-whip/musical-chairs] The term "playing musical chairs" is also a metaphor for describing any activity where items or people are repeatedly and usually pointlessly shuffled among various locations or positions.
[src:crack-the-whip/musical-chairs] It can also refer to a condition where people have to expend time searching for a resource, such as having to travel from one gasoline station to another when there is a shortage.
[src:crack-the-whip/musical-chairs] It may also refer to political situations where one leader replaces another, only to be rapidly replaced due to the instability of the governing system (see cabinet reshuffle).
[src:crack-the-whip/musical-chairs] The game is featured in the original incarnation of the Andrew Lloyd Webber musical, *Evita*, during the number *"The Art of the Possible"*, wherein it serves as a symbolic metaphor of Juan Perón's rise to power.
[src:crack-the-whip/musical-chairs] In this sequence, Peron and a number of military officers play the game, which the former wins.
[src:crack-the-whip/musical-chairs] The game is used on the lenten special of *Sunday PinaSaya* entitled "Trip to Jerusalem" aired on GMA Network on April 9, 2017.
[src:crack-the-whip/musical-chairs] It featured the young girl Jessie (played by Barbie Forteza).
[src:crack-the-whip/snap-the-whip] Homer spent several summers in New York's Hudson Valley, and is said to have been inspired to paint this scene by local boys playing at the Hurley schoolhouse.
[src:crack-the-whip/snap-the-whip] The first version is in the Butler Institute of American Art in Youngstown, Ohio.
[src:crack-the-whip/snap-the-whip] Homer painted a second version, of similar date, which is now in the Metropolitan Museum of Art, New York.
[src:crack-the-whip/snap-the-whip] In this, he retains the schoolhouse but the background hillscape is removed, making the location less regionally specific.
[src:crack-the-whip/winslow-homer] Largely self-taught, Homer began his career working as a commercial illustrator.
[src:crack-the-whip/winslow-homer] He subsequently took up oil painting and produced major studio works characterized by the weight and density he exploited from the medium.
[src:crack-the-whip/winslow-homer] He also worked extensively in watercolor, creating a fluid and prolific œuvre, primarily chronicling his working vacations.
[src:crack-the-whip/winslow-homer] Homer was born in Boston, Massachusetts, on February 24, 1836, the second of three sons of Charles Savage Homer and Henrietta Maria Benson Homer, both from long lines of New Englanders.
[src:crack-the-whip/winslow-homer] His mother was a gifted amateur watercolorist and Homer's first teacher.
[src:crack-the-whip/winslow-homer] She and her son had a close relationship throughout their lives.
[src:crack-the-whip/winslow-homer] Homer took on many of her traits, including her quiet, strong-willed, terse, sociable nature, her dry sense of humor, and her artistic talent.
[src:crack-the-whip/winslow-homer] Homer had a happy childhood, growing up mostly in then-rural Cambridge, Massachusetts.
[src:crack-the-whip/winslow-homer] He was an average student, but his art talent was evident in his early years.
[src:crack-the-whip/winslow-homer] Homer's father was a volatile, restless businessman who was always looking to "make a killing".
[src:crack-the-whip/winslow-homer] When Homer was 13 years old, Charles gave up the hardware store business to seek a fortune in the California gold rush.
[src:crack-the-whip/winslow-homer] When that failed, Charles left his family and went to Europe to raise capital for other get-rich-quick schemes that did not pay off.
[src:crack-the-whip/winslow-homer] After Homer's high school graduation, his father saw a newspaper advertisement and arranged for an apprenticeship.
[src:crack-the-whip/winslow-homer] Homer's apprenticeship at the age of 19 to J.
[src:crack-the-whip/winslow-homer] Bufford, a Boston commercial lithographer, was a formative but "treadmill experience".
[src:crack-the-whip/winslow-homer] He worked repetitively on sheet music covers and other commercial work for two years.
[src:crack-the-whip/winslow-homer] By 1857, his freelance career was underway after he turned down an offer to join the staff of *Harper's Weekly*.
[src:crack-the-whip/winslow-homer] "From the time I took my nose off that lithographic stone," Homer later stated, "I have had no master, and never shall have any." Homer opened his own studio in Boston.
[src:crack-the-whip/winslow-homer] Homer's career as an illustrator lasted nearly twenty years.
[src:crack-the-whip/winslow-homer] He contributed illustrations of Boston life and rural New England life to magazines such as *Ballou's Pictorial* and *Harper's Weekly* at a time when the market for illustrations was growing rapidly and fads and fashions were changing quickly.
[src:crack-the-whip/winslow-homer] His early works, mostly commercial wood engravings of urban and country social scenes, are characterized by clean outlines, simplified forms, dramatic contrast of light and dark, and lively figure groupings—qualities that remained important throughout his career.
[src:crack-the-whip/winslow-homer] His quick success was mostly due to this strong understanding of graphic design and also to the adaptability of his designs to wood engraving.
[src:crack-the-whip/winslow-homer] Before moving to New York City in 1859, Homer lived in Belmont, Massachusetts, with his family.
[src:crack-the-whip/winslow-homer] His uncle's Belmont mansion, the 1853 Homer House, was the inspiration for a number of his early illustrations and paintings, including several of his 1860s croquet pictures.
[src:crack-the-whip/winslow-homer] The Homer House, owned by the Belmont Woman's Club, is open for public tours.
[src:crack-the-whip/winslow-homer] Homer Jr., a Harvard-educated chemist, was hired by Lawson Valentine to work for the paint company Valentine & Co, later known as Valspar.
[src:crack-the-whip/winslow-homer] Lawson Valentine became important to Winslow Homer as an early and significant collector of his work, later providing him with a studio at their farm in New York.
[src:crack-the-whip/winslow-homer] In 1859, he opened a studio in the Tenth Street Studio Building in New York City, the artistic and publishing capital of the United States.
[src:crack-the-whip/winslow-homer] Until 1863, he attended classes at the National Academy of Design, and studied briefly with Frederick Rondel, who taught him the basics of painting.
[src:crack-the-whip/winslow-homer] In only about a year of self-training, Homer was producing excellent oil work.
[src:crack-the-whip/winslow-homer] His mother tried to raise family funds to send him to Europe for further study but instead *Harper's* sent Homer to the front lines of the American Civil War (1861–1865), where he sketched battle scenes and camp life, the quiet moments as well as the chaotic ones.
[src:crack-the-whip/winslow-homer] His initial sketches were of the camp, commanders, and army of the famous Union officer, Major General George B.
[src:crack-the-whip/winslow-homer] McClellan, at the banks of the Potomac River in October 1861.
[src:crack-the-whip/winslow-homer] Although the drawings did not get much attention at the time, they mark Homer's expanding skills from illustrator to painter.
[src:crack-the-whip/winslow-homer] As with his urban scenes, Homer illustrated women during wartime, and showed the effects of the war on the home front.
[src:crack-the-whip/winslow-homer] The war work was dangerous and exhausting.
[src:crack-the-whip/winslow-homer] Back at his studio, Homer would regain his strength and re-focus his artistic vision.
[src:crack-the-whip/winslow-homer] He set to work on a series of war-related paintings based on his sketches, among them *Sharpshooter on Picket Duty* (1862), *Home, Sweet Home* (1863), and *Prisoners from the Front* (1866).
[src:crack-the-whip/winslow-homer] He exhibited paintings of these subjects every year at the National Academy of Design from 1863 to 1866.
[src:crack-the-whip/winslow-homer] *Home, Sweet Home* was shown at the National Academy to particular critical acclaim; it was quickly sold and the artist was consequently elected an Associate Academician, then a full Academician in 1865.
[src:crack-the-whip/winslow-homer] During this time, he also continued to sell his illustrations to periodicals such as *Our Young Folks* and *Frank Leslie's Chimney Corner*.
[src:crack-the-whip/winslow-homer] After the American Civil War, Homer turned his attention primarily to scenes of childhood and young women, reflecting nostalgia for simpler times, both his own and the nation’s as a whole.
[src:crack-the-whip/winslow-homer] Homer was also interested in postwar subject matter that conveyed the silent tension between two communities seeking to understand their future.
[src:crack-the-whip/winslow-homer] His oil painting *A Visit from the Old Mistress* (1876) shows an encounter between a group of four freed slaves and their former mistress.
[src:crack-the-whip/winslow-homer] The formal equivalence between the standing figures suggests the balance that the nation hoped to find in the difficult years of Reconstruction.
[src:crack-the-whip/winslow-homer] Homer composed this painting from sketches he had made while traveling through Virginia.
[src:crack-the-whip/winslow-homer] Near the beginning of his painting career, the 27-year-old Homer demonstrated a maturity of feeling, depth of perception, and mastery of technique which was immediately recognized.
[src:crack-the-whip/winslow-homer] His realism was objective, true to nature, and emotionally controlled.
[src:crack-the-whip/winslow-homer] One critic wrote, "Winslow Homer is one of those few young artists who make a decided impression of their power with their very first contributions to the Academy ...
[src:crack-the-whip/winslow-homer] He at this moment wields a better pencil, models better, colors better, than many whom, were it not improper, we could mention as regular contributors to the Academy." And of *Home, Sweet Home* specifically, "There is no clap-trap about it.
[src:crack-the-whip/winslow-homer] The delicacy and strength of emotion which reign throughout this little picture are not surpassed in the whole exhibition." "It is a work of real feeling, soldiers in camp listening to the evening band, and thinking of the wives and darlings far away.
[src:crack-the-whip/winslow-homer] Before exhibiting at the National Academy of Design, Homer finally traveled to Paris, France, in 1867 where he remained for a year.
[src:crack-the-whip/winslow-homer] His most praised early painting, *Prisoners from the Front*, was on exhibit at the Exposition Universelle in Paris at the same time.
[src:crack-the-whip/winslow-homer] He did not study formally but he practiced landscape painting while continuing to work for *Harper's*, depicting scenes of Parisian life.
[src:crack-the-whip/winslow-homer] Homer painted approximately one dozen small paintings during the stay.
[src:crack-the-whip/winslow-homer] Although he arrived in France at a time of new fashions in art, Homer's main subject for his paintings was peasant life, showing more of an alignment with the established French Barbizon school and the artist Millet than with newer artists Manet and Courbet.
[src:crack-the-whip/winslow-homer] Though his interest in depicting natural light parallels that of the early impressionists, there is no evidence of direct influence as he was already a plein-air painter in America and had already evolved a personal style which was much closer to Manet than Monet.
[src:crack-the-whip/winslow-homer] Homer was very private about his personal life and his methods (even denying his first biographer any personal information or commentary), but his stance was clearly one of independence of style and a devotion to American subjects.
[src:crack-the-whip/winslow-homer] Throughout the 1870s, Homer continued painting mostly rural or idyllic scenes of farm life, children playing, and young adults courting, including *Country School* (1871) and *The Morning Bell* (1872).
[src:crack-the-whip/winslow-homer] In 1875, Homer quit working as a commercial illustrator and vowed to survive on his paintings and watercolors alone.
[src:crack-the-whip/winslow-homer] Despite his excellent critical reputation, his finances continued to remain precarious.
[src:crack-the-whip/winslow-homer] His popular 1872 painting *Snap the Whip* was exhibited at the 1876 Centennial Exposition in Philadelphia, Pennsylvania, as was one of his finest and most famous paintings, *Breezing Up* (1876).
[src:crack-the-whip/winslow-homer] *Breezing Up*, Homer's iconic painting of a father and three boys out for a spirited sail, received wide praise.
[src:crack-the-whip/winslow-homer] The *New York Tribune* wrote, "There is no picture in this exhibition, nor can we remember when there has been a picture in any exhibition, that can be named alongside this." Visits to Petersburg, Virginia, around 1876 resulted in paintings of rural African American life.
[src:crack-the-whip/winslow-homer] The same straightforward sensibility which allowed Homer to distill art from these potentially sentimental subjects also yielded the most unaffected views of African American life at the time, as illustrated in *Dressing for the Carnival* (1877) and *A Visit from the Old Mistress* (1876).
[src:crack-the-whip/winslow-homer] In 1877, Homer exhibited for the first time at the Boston Art Club with the oil painting, *An Afternoon Sun*, (owned by the Artist).
[src:crack-the-whip/winslow-homer] In 1878 Homer spent a particularly productive year as the guest of industrialist Lawson Valentine at his property in the Adirondack Mountains, Houghton Farm.
[src:crack-the-whip/winslow-homer] From 1877 through 1909, Homer exhibited often at the Boston Art Club.
[src:crack-the-whip/winslow-homer] Works on paper, both drawings and watercolors, were frequently exhibited by Homer beginning in 1882.
[src:crack-the-whip/winslow-homer] A most unusual sculpture by the Artist, *Hunter with Dog – Northwoods*, was exhibited in 1902.
[src:crack-the-whip/winslow-homer] By that year, Homer had switched his primary Gallery from the Boston-based Doll and Richards to the New York City based Knoedler & Co.
[src:crack-the-whip/winslow-homer] Homer became a member of The Tile Club, a group of artists and writers who met frequently to exchange ideas and organize outings for painting, as well as foster the creation of decorative tiles.
[src:crack-the-whip/winslow-homer] For a short time, he designed tiles for fireplaces.
[src:crack-the-whip/winslow-homer] Homer's nickname in The Tile Club was "The Obtuse Bard".
[src:crack-the-whip/winslow-homer] Other well known Tilers were painters William Merritt Chase, Arthur Quartley, and the sculptor Augustus Saint Gaudens.
[src:crack-the-whip/winslow-homer] Homer started painting with watercolors on a regular basis in 1873 during a summer stay in Gloucester, Massachusetts.
[src:crack-the-whip/winslow-homer] From the beginning, his technique was natural, fluid and confident, demonstrating his innate talent for a difficult medium.
[src:crack-the-whip/winslow-homer] Here, again, the critics were puzzled at first, "A child with an ink bottle could not have done worse." Another critic said that Homer "made a sudden and desperate plunge into water color painting".
[src:crack-the-whip/winslow-homer] But his watercolors proved popular and enduring, and sold more readily, improving his financial condition considerably.
[src:crack-the-whip/winslow-homer] They varied from highly detailed (*Blackboard* – 1877) to broadly impressionistic (*Schooner at Sunset* – 1880).
[src:crack-the-whip/winslow-homer] Some watercolors were made as preparatory sketches for oil paintings (as for "Breezing Up") and some as finished works in themselves.
[src:crack-the-whip/winslow-homer] Thereafter, he seldom traveled without paper, brushes and water based paints.
[src:crack-the-whip/winslow-homer] As a result of disappointments with women or from some other emotional turmoil, Homer became reclusive in the late 1870s, no longer enjoying urban social life and living instead in Gloucester.
[src:crack-the-whip/winslow-homer] For a while, he even lived in secluded Eastern Point Lighthouse (with the keeper's family).
[src:crack-the-whip/winslow-homer] In re-establishing his love of the sea, Homer found a rich source of themes while closely observing the fishermen, the sea, and the marine weather.
[src:crack-the-whip/winslow-homer] After 1880, he rarely featured genteel women at leisure, focusing instead on working women.
[src:crack-the-whip/winslow-homer] Homer spent two years (1881–1882) in the coastal village of Cullercoats, Northumberland.
[src:crack-the-whip/winslow-homer] Many of the paintings at Cullercoats took as their subjects working men and women and their daily heroism, imbued with a solidity and sobriety which was new to Homer's art, presaging the direction of his future work.
[src:crack-the-whip/winslow-homer] He wrote, "The women are the working bees.
[src:crack-the-whip/winslow-homer] Stout hardy creatures." His works from this period are almost exclusively watercolors.
[src:crack-the-whip/winslow-homer] His palette became constrained and sober; his paintings larger, more ambitious, and more deliberately conceived and executed.
[src:crack-the-whip/winslow-homer] His subjects more universal and less nationalistic, more heroic by virtue of his unsentimental rendering.
[src:crack-the-whip/winslow-homer] Although he moved away from the spontaneity and bright innocence of the American paintings of the 1860s and 1870s, Homer found a new style and vision which carried his talent into new realms.
[src:crack-the-whip/winslow-homer] Back in the U.S. in November 1882, Homer showed his English watercolors in New York.
[src:crack-the-whip/winslow-homer] Critics noticed the change in style at once, "He is a very different Homer from the one we knew in days gone by", now his pictures "touch a far higher plane ...
[src:crack-the-whip/winslow-homer] They are works of High Art." Homer's women were no longer "dolls who flaunt their millinery" but "sturdy, fearless, fit wives and mothers of men" who are fully capable of enduring the forces and vagaries of nature alongside their men.
[src:crack-the-whip/winslow-homer] In 1883, Homer moved to Prouts Neck, Maine (in Scarborough), and lived at his family's estate in the remodeled carriage house seventy-five feet from the ocean.
[src:crack-the-whip/winslow-homer] During the rest of the mid-1880s, Homer painted his monumental sea scenes.
[src:crack-the-whip/winslow-homer] In *Undertow* (1886), depicting the dramatic rescue of two female bathers by two male lifeguards, Homer's figures "have the weight and authority of classical figures".
[src:crack-the-whip/winslow-homer] In *Eight Bells* (1886), two sailors carefully take their bearings on deck, calmly appraising their position and by extension, their relationship with the sea; they are confident in their seamanship but respectful of the forces before them.
[src:crack-the-whip/winslow-homer] Other notable paintings among these dramatic struggle-with-nature images are *Banks Fisherman*, *The Gulf Stream*, *Rum Cay*, *Mending the Nets*, and *Searchlight on Harbor Entrance, Santiago de Cuba*.
[src:crack-the-whip/winslow-homer] At fifty years of age, Homer had become a "Yankee Robinson Crusoe, cloistered on his art island" and "a hermit with a brush".
[src:crack-the-whip/winslow-homer] Many of the sea pictures took years to sell and *Undertow* only earned him $400.
[src:crack-the-whip/winslow-homer] In these years, Homer received emotional sustenance primarily from his mother, brother Charles, and sister-in-law Martha ("Mattie").
[src:crack-the-whip/winslow-homer] After his mother's death, Homer became a "parent" for his aging but domineering father and Mattie became his closest female intimate.
[src:crack-the-whip/winslow-homer] In the winters of 1884–5, Homer ventured to warmer locations in Florida, Cuba, and the Bahamas and did a series of watercolors as part of a commission for *Century Magazine*.
[src:crack-the-whip/winslow-homer] He replaced the turbulent green storm-tossed sea of Prouts Neck with the sparkling blue skies of the Caribbean and the hardy New Englanders with Black natives, further expanding his watercolor technique, subject matter, and palette.
[src:crack-the-whip/winslow-homer] During this trip he painted *Children Under a Palm Tree* for Edith Blake, the wife of Henry Arthur Blake, the then-governor of The Bahamas.
[src:crack-the-whip/winslow-homer] His tropical stays inspired and refreshed him in much the same way as Paul Gauguin's trips to Tahiti.
[src:crack-the-whip/winslow-homer] Homer frequently visited Key West, Florida, between 1888 and 1903.
[src:crack-the-whip/winslow-homer] Some of his best-known works, *A Norther, Key West, The Gulf Stream, Taking on Wet Provisions,* and *Palms in the Storm*, are said to have been produced there.
[src:crack-the-whip/winslow-homer] Homer found inspiration in summer trips to the North Woods Club, near the hamlet of Minerva, New York, in the Adirondack Mountains.
[src:crack-the-whip/winslow-homer] It was on these fishing vacations that he experimented with the watercolor medium, producing works of the utmost vigor and subtlety, hymns to solitude, nature, and to outdoor life.
[src:crack-the-whip/winslow-homer] Homer does not shrink from the savagery of blood sports nor the struggle for survival.
[src:crack-the-whip/winslow-homer] The color effects are boldly and facilely applied.
[src:crack-the-whip/winslow-homer] In 1893, Homer painted one of his most famous "Darwinian" works, *The Fox Hunt*, which depicts a flock of starving crows descending on a fox slowed by deep snow.
[src:crack-the-whip/winslow-homer] This was Homer's largest painting, and it was immediately purchased by the Pennsylvania Academy of the Fine Arts, his first painting in a major American museum collection.
[src:crack-the-whip/winslow-homer] In *Huntsman and Dogs* (1891), a lone, impassive hunter, with his yelping dogs at his side, heads home after a hunt with deer skins slung over his right shoulder.
[src:crack-the-whip/winslow-homer] Another late work, *The Gulf Stream* (1899), shows a black sailor adrift in a damaged boat, surrounded by sharks as a waterspout approaches.
[src:crack-the-whip/winslow-homer] By 1900, Homer finally reached financial stability, as his paintings fetched good prices from museums and he began to receive rents from real estate properties.
[src:crack-the-whip/winslow-homer] He also became free of the responsibilities of caring for his father, who had died two years earlier.
[src:crack-the-whip/winslow-homer] Homer continued producing excellent watercolors, mostly on trips to Canada and the Caribbean.
[src:crack-the-whip/winslow-homer] Other late works include sporting scenes such as *Right and Left*, as well as seascapes absent of human figures, mostly of waves crashing against rocks in varying light.
[src:crack-the-whip/winslow-homer] His late seascapes are especially valued for their dramatic and forceful expression of nature's powers, and for their beauty and intensity.
[src:crack-the-whip/winslow-homer] Homer died in 1910 at the age of 74 in his Prouts Neck studio and was interred in the Mount Auburn Cemetery in Cambridge, Massachusetts.
[src:crack-the-whip/winslow-homer] His painting, *Shooting the Rapids, Saguenay River*, remains unfinished.
[src:crack-the-whip/winslow-homer] His Prouts Neck studio, a National Historic Landmark, is now owned by the Portland Museum of Art, which offers tours.
[src:crack-the-whip/winslow-homer] Homer never taught in a school or privately, as did Thomas Eakins, but his works strongly influenced succeeding generations of American painters for their direct and energetic interpretation of man's stoic relationship to an often neutral and sometimes harsh wilderness.
[src:crack-the-whip/winslow-homer] Robert Henri called Homer's work an "integrity of nature".
[src:crack-the-whip/winslow-homer] American illustrator and teacher Howard Pyle revered Homer and encouraged his students to study him.
[src:crack-the-whip/winslow-homer] Wyeth (and through him Andrew Wyeth and Jamie Wyeth), shared the influence and appreciation, even following Homer to Maine for inspiration.
[src:crack-the-whip/winslow-homer] The elder Wyeth's respect for his antecedent was "intense and absolute" and can be observed in his early work *Mowing* (1907).
[src:crack-the-whip/winslow-homer] Post Office released a commemorative stamp honoring Winslow Homer.
[src:crack-the-whip/winslow-homer] Homer's famous oil painting *Breezing Up*, now hanging in the National Gallery in Washington DC, was chosen as the image for the design of this issue.
[src:crack-the-whip/winslow-homer] On August 12, 2010, The Postal Service issued a 44-cent commemorative stamp featuring Homer's *Boys in a Pasture* at the APS Stamp Show in Richmond, Virginia.
[src:crack-the-whip/winslow-homer] This stamp was the ninth to be issued in a series entitled "American Treasures".
[src:crack-the-whip/winslow-homer] The original painting is part of the Hayden Collection at the Museum of Fine Arts in Boston.
[src:crack-the-whip/winslow-homer] It depicts two boys from Belmont, Massachusetts—John Carney and Patrick Keenan—who posed for the artist for 75 cents per day.
[src:crack-the-whip/winslow-homer] His work was part of the painting event in the art competition at the 1932 Summer Olympics.
[src:crack-the-whip/winslow-homer] Pastoral landscapes and lifestyle (see pastoralism) is a genre of literature, art and music that depicts shepherds herding livestock around open areas of land according to seasons and the changing availability of water and pasturage.
[src:crack-the-whip/winslow-homer] Winslow Homer's paintings often depicted marine landscapes.
[src:crack-the-whip/winslow-homer] Later, when Winslow Homer spent the years between 1881 and 1882 in the village of Cullercoats, Tyne and Wear, his paintings depicting shores and coastal landscapes changed.
[src:crack-the-whip/winslow-homer] Many of the paintings from the English coast have as subjects working men and women from the area.
